## SPIRE - the reference implementation

**SPIRE** = SPIFFE Runtime Environment. CNCF graduated. The control plane that issues and verifies SVIDs.

### Components

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    subgraph control [Control plane]
        server["SPIRE Server (HA)<br/>signing CA, registration registry,<br/>node attestor plugins, datastore"]
    end
    subgraph node1 [Node 1]
        agent1[SPIRE Agent]
        wl1[Workload]
    end
    subgraph node2 [Node 2]
        agent2[SPIRE Agent]
        wl2[Workload]
    end
    server <-- "mTLS (agent SVID)" --> agent1
    server <-- "mTLS (agent SVID)" --> agent2
    agent1 -- "Workload API (UDS, no auth)" --> wl1
    agent2 -- "Workload API (UDS, no auth)" --> wl2
```

### Two-level attestation - the core mechanism

This is what makes SPIRE distinct from credential-based systems.

| Level | Question | Evidence |
|---|---|---|
| **Node attestation** | Is this a legitimate node I should trust to run an Agent? | Cloud IID (AWS EC2 instance identity doc, GCP IIT, Azure MSI), Kubernetes PSAT, TPM, ephemeral join token, x509 PoP |
| **Workload attestation** | Is the process calling the Workload API actually the workload it claims to be? | Linux UID/GID, `/proc` inspection, Kubernetes pod labels/namespace/SA, **container image digest**, systemd unit name |

Neither level uses a pre-shared secret. Both are rooted in platform-level evidence an unauthorized process cannot forge.

### Registration entries

Selectors → SPIFFE ID:

```bash
spire-server entry create \
  -parentID  spiffe://prod.example.com/node/k8s-worker-1 \
  -spiffeID  spiffe://prod.example.com/ns/payments/sa/checkout \
  -selector  k8s:ns:payments \
  -selector  k8s:sa:checkout \
  -selector  k8s:container-image:registry.example.com/checkout@sha256:abc...
```

The image-digest selector is a strong primitive for supply-chain-aware identity - it defeats image-tag drift.

### Deployment topologies

- **Single-cluster** - one SPIRE Server, agents as a DaemonSet. Default for most Kubernetes deployments.
- **Nested SPIRE** - root server with downstream servers as intermediate CAs. Useful for multi-cluster with local autonomy under a single trust domain.
- **Federated** - multiple independent trust domains exchanging bundles. Multi-org or strict environment isolation.
- **HA** - multiple Servers behind an LB, sharing a SQL datastore (Postgres/MySQL) and an upstream CA (Vault PKI, AWS Private CA, Google CAS, cert-manager).

### Upstream authorities

In production, almost always use an `UpstreamAuthority` plugin so SPIRE Server is an intermediate CA, not the root. Keeps the real root offline/HSM-protected and integrates with existing PKI.

